    "Background": {
      "text": "Always assess for associated head, face, and neck injuries",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Nasal deformity, bony crepitus\nProfuse\nepistaxis\nPeriorbital ecchymosis in the absence of other findings of orbital injury",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "epistaxis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Epistaxis"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Pediatric_Considerations": {
      "text": "More cartilage present\nSeptal hematomas\nare more common, as nasal septum is more at risk of injury\nInjuries heal more quickly, requiring followup in 7-10 days, whereas adults should seek specialist care in 2 weeks.",
